me agents may demonstrate a prolonged elimination half-life (e.g., fluoxetine). If serotonin syndrome develops or is suspected during the course of therapy, all serotonergic agents should be discontinued immediately and supportive care rendered as necessary. Moderately ill patients may also benefit from the administration of a serotonin antagonist (e.g., cyproheptadine, chlorpromazine). Severe cases should be managed under consultation with a toxicologist and may require sedation, neuromuscular paralysis, intubation, and mechanical ventilation in addition to the other measures.', 'Synergism', 'Benzonatate, Dalfampridine, Tafamidis, Pitolisant, Riluzole', NULL, 'Major', NULL, 'DDInter', 'pharmacodynamic', NULL, 'https://ddinter2.scbdd.com/server/interact/3949/', '[1] "Product Information. Zyvox (linezolid)" Pharmacia and Upjohn, Kalamazoo, MI.[2] DeBellis RJ, Schaefer OP, Liquori M, Volturo GA "Linezolid-associated serotonin syndrome after concomitant treatment with citalopram and mirtazepine in a critically ill bone marrow transplant recipient." J Intensive Care Med 20 (2005): 351-3[3] Turkel SB, Nadala JG, Wincor MZ "Possible serotonin syndrome in association with 5-HT3 antagonist agents." Psychosomatics 42 (2001): 258-60[4] Taylor JJ, Wilson JW, Estes LL "Linezolid and serotonergic drug interactions: a retrospective survey." Clin Infect Dis 43 (2006): 180-7[5] Fischer P "Serotonin syndrome in the elderly after antidepressive monotherapy." J Clin Psychopharmacol 15 (1995): 440-2[6] Margolese HC, Chouinard G "Serotonin syndrome from addition of low-dose trazodone to nefazodone." Am J Psychiatry 157 (2000): 1022[7] Mills KC "Serotonin syndrome: A clinical update." Crit Care Clin 13 (1997): 763[8] "Product Information. Luvox (fluvoxamine)." Solvay Pharmaceuticals Inc, Marietta, GA.[9] Steinberg M, Morin AK "Mild serotonin syndrome associated with concurrent linezolid and fluoxetine." Am J Health Syst Pharm 64 (2007): 59-62[10] "Product Information. Prozac (fluoxetine)